---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE } from '../consts';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <BaseHead
      title={`About · ${SITE_TITLE}`}
      description="Why this site exists and what kind of work it documents."
    />
  </head>
  <body>
    <Header />
    <main class="prose">
      <section class="hero">
        <span class="eyebrow">About</span>
        <div>
          <h1>A publishing space for software built by AI, or built by humans working with AI.</h1>
          <p>
            This site exists to share the results, process, and lessons behind projects where AI is not just a toy,
            but an actual participant in making software.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>
      <article>
        <p>
          Sometimes the work is generated mostly by an AI agent. Sometimes a human directs the work,
          reviews it, corrects it, and shapes it into something publishable. Most of the interesting cases
          live somewhere in between. That middle ground is what this site is for.
        </p>

        <p>
          The goal is not to pretend that AI did everything alone, and not to reduce the human role to a footnote.
          The goal is to document what was actually made, how it was made, what the collaboration looked like,
          and whether the result was worth the effort.
        </p>

        <h2>Why publish this kind of work?</h2>
        <p>
          Because a lot of AI-assisted development currently disappears into chat history, private repos,
          and demos with no durable record. That makes it hard to learn from real examples. A public archive
          creates a better paper trail: what prompts worked, what architecture decisions were made,
          where AI was genuinely useful, and where a human still had to take the wheel.
        </p>

        <p>
          There is also a softer reason: this kind of work deserves context. "Built with AI" is not very informative.
          It can mean autocomplete, an agent doing scaffolding, a human delegating implementation,
          or a much more involved back-and-forth. Publishing the surrounding explanation makes the output more credible,
          and more useful to anyone trying to do similar work.
        </p>

        <h2>What belongs here?</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>projects created directly by AI agents</li>
          <li>projects developed by humans through AI delegation and review</li>
          <li>build logs, postmortems, and implementation notes</li>
          <li>before/after writeups showing how a rough AI draft became a real product</li>
          <li>tooling experiments around agent workflows, browser automation, and code generation</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>The point</h2>
        <p>
          The point is not hype. It is evidence.
          A site like this can show what AI-assisted development actually looks like when it leaves the lab,
          hits constraints, gets revised by humans, and turns into something other people can inspect.
        </p>

        <p>
          If the current era of software is going to involve humans and AI building together,
          then it is worth keeping a record of the artifacts, the workflow, and the judgment calls that shaped them.
          That is the reason this site exists.
        </p>
      </article>
    </main>
    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
